<opener><dateline><date>14th May 1916</date></dateline> <address><addrLine>Ernest Blythe, Esq.,</addrLine>
<addrLine>No. 3134 Brixton Prison. S. W.</addrLine></address> <salute>Dear Mr Blythe:-</salute></opener> <p>I have just received your letter and am very sorry for <lb/> your plight. You should send in a full statement on the lines <lb/> of your letter to me. I am defending Sir Roger Casement and am <lb/> utterly unable to go to Brixton or indeed to take up any other  <lb/>new work. I shall ask Mr MacDonnell, solicitor and nephew of <lb/> Lord McDee to go and see you instead of me and I know he will do <lb/> do. I am very sorry indeed I really can't do more. You must not be <lb/> sanguine of success as the authorities and the public still think the <lb/> Sinn Fein and the rebellion are synonymous and won't believe the  <lb/>contrary.</p> <closer><salute>Yours sincerely,</salute> <signed>G. Gavan Duffy.</signed></closer>
        
    

    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        

         

